The United States' tech war against China.
Made in New York — the worst diplomatic decision ever made by the United States (or even earlier generations) is the "war of choice" in 2003 against Iraq, which claimed to be the intention of eliminating — non-existent — large-scale weapons of mass destruction.
However, the necessity of understanding the flawed logic behind this disastrous decision has never been more pressing, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar misguided US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic then-US Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that even a small risk (such as 1%) of WMDs falling into the hands of terrorists was a sufficient reason to take action in anticipation of such an event.
However, this way of reasoning almost always leads to erroneous decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are currently using Cheneysism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the US government's view, since we cannot be sure that Chinese technology is safe, we should approach and ban it as if it is definitely harmful.
Accurate decision-making will apply probability estimation to each alternative measure.
People who lived a generation ago would have viewed the policymakers's consideration of a 1% risk of nuclear weapons falling into the hands of terrorists and a 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed assumptions as irresponsible.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) distracted the public attention, letting people overlook the fact that the Iraq war lacked legitimacy and would severely destabilize the Middle East and the global politics.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not just that it acts on the basis of relatively small risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but that politicians will often whip up fear for reasons that are not clearly stated.
This is what US leaders are doing again: stirring up fear about Chinese tech companies by pointing out and exaggerating some minor risks.
One of the most relevant (but not the only) cases is the U.S. government's attack on the telecommunications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually shutting down the company's domestic market and endeavoring to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the United States may ultimately trigger a entirely unwarranted geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological advancements because I believe 5G and other digital technologies can provide enormous momentum for eradicating poverty and achieving other UN sustainable development goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to step up its actions towards the Sustainable Development Goals.
I once wrote a brief foreword for a report on the topic concerning Huawei (without compensation) and was subsequently criticized by those hostile to China for it. I then inquired of industry leaders and government officials whether there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in any improper conduct, and repeatedly received the answer that Huawei's behavior was no different from that of other reputable industry leaders.
Despite this, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may harm global security.
US officials claim that "backdoors" in Huawei software or hardware may allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance globally.
They point out that the law in China requires Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are now right here.
Huawei's 5G devices are priced low in quality, currently leading many competitors and have already begun to promote.
Its high performance originates from massive investments in R&D over the years, scale economy effects, and its experience of climbing up in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to its sustainable development, it would be foolish for low-income economies around the world to reject the early rollout of 5G.
However, despite having no evidence of any backdoor existence, the US is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The Americans' claim is universal.
As an FCC commissioner from the US once said: "Countries with 5G will have relevant innovation and set the standards for the rest of the world, and it is unlikely that the US will be one of them."
Other countries — — especially the UK — — have yet to find any backdoors in Huawei's hardware and software.
Even if a backdoor is discovered in the future, it is almost certain to be closed at that time.
The debate about Huawei in Germany is also getting loud, because the US government threatened that unless the authorities block Huawei's 5G technology, intelligence cooperation will be reduced.
Perhaps under pressure from the United States, the head of the German Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution recently made a statement similar to that of Cheney: "Infrastructure is not a field that is suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted to intervene."
But he was also unable to produce any specific evidence of wrongdoing.
Compared to that, Chancellor Merkel has been waging a behind-the-scenes battle to open the market to Huawei.
But ironically, US complaints actually partly reflect US surveillance activities at home and abroad - though this is no longer news.
Chinese-made equipment may make it harder for the US government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's unjust surveillance activities should be stopped.
Independent oversight conducted by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In essence, we should choose diplomacy and institutional protection rather than engaging in a technical war.
The U.S. demand to ban Huawei's impact is not limited to the early adoption of 5G networks, but also poses a huge risk to rule-based trading systems.
The United States is no longer an undisputed global technology leader today, and neither US President Trump nor his advisors want to compete based on a rules-based system.
Their goal is to curb China's technological rise.
They also attempted to destroy the organization by crippling its dispute resolution mechanism, which is a manifestation of their attitude toward global rules.
If the Trump administration can "succeed" in dividing the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts would increase exponentially.
After World War II, the United States promoted free trade, not only to raise global efficiency and expand the U.S. technology market, but also to reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
One of the contributing factors to the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the U.S. under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression, led to the rise of Hitler, and ultimately triggered the outbreak of World War II.
As it is in other fields, sparking fear and taking action rather than following evidence in the realm of international affairs is a path leading to destruction.
Let us persist in reason, evidence, and rules; this is the safest method.
Let us establish independent monitoring institutions to reduce the threat of any country using the global network to monitor other countries or launch cyber warfare.
With this in place, the world can quickly leverage breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
